# Infrastructure as Code — {{companyName}}

## When to Use
- Defining cloud infrastructure with Terraform, CDK, or Pulumi
- Managing state files and backend configurations
- Reviewing or modifying infrastructure modules

## Terraform Conventions
- One module per logical component (networking, compute, database)
- Use variables.tf, outputs.tf, main.tf structure
- Pin provider versions in required_providers
- Store state in remote backend (S3, GCS, Azure Blob)
- Use workspaces or directory structure for environment separation

## AWS CDK Conventions
- One stack per bounded context
- Use constructs for reusable patterns
- Pin CDK version in package.json
- Run `cdk diff` before `cdk deploy`
- Use context values for environment-specific config

## Best Practices
- Always run `terraform plan` / `cdk diff` before applying changes
- Never store secrets in IaC files — use Secret Manager references
- Tag all resources with standard labels (env, team, cost-center)
- Write integration tests for infrastructure modules
- Document module interfaces with clear input/output descriptions
